function gcd

calculates greatest common of two numbers divisor using the Euclidean algorithm.

  1. Input (a, b)
    1. a: positive integer and dimension = 1
    2. b: positive integer and dimension = 1
  2. check both numbers whether is numerical. [if (is.numeric(a) | is.numeric(b) == FALSE)]
    1. (if) one or two of them is not numerical number -> stop with an error message
    2. (else) go to next step
  3. check both numbers whether is positive integer. [if (a <= 0 | b <= 0 | a%%1 != 0 | b%%1 != 0)]
    1. (if) one or two of them is not positive integer -> stop with an error message
    2. (else) go to next step
  4. use while (b != 0) loop
    1. using the Euclidean algorithm.
    2. change (a, b) -> (b, a%%b) again and again
    3. when b = 0 end
  5. after the while loop, we get (a<- the greatest common divisor, b<-0).
    1. return (a), which is output
    2. output is a positive integer.

gcd_flowchart

gcd(1071, 462)
## [1] 21
gcd(462, 1071)
## [1] 21

## [1] 38

try(gcd(-1, 12))
## Error in gcd(-1, 12) : inputs should be positive integers

gcd_three

calculates greatest common of three numbers divisor using the Euclidean algorithm.

  1. input(a, b, c)
    1. a: positive integer and dimension = 1
    2. b: positive integer and dimension = 1
    3. c: positive integer and dimension = 1
  2. use gcd function we create before
    1. find the greatest common divisor of (a, b), and store in a new variable named cd_two. [cd_two = gcd(a,b)]
  3. use gcd function we create before
    1. find the greatest common divisor of (new variable, c). [gcd(c,cd_two)]
    2. then we return the greatest divisor of (a, b, c).
    3. output: positive integer.

gcd_three_flowchart

gcd_three(1071, 462, 4452)
## [1] 21
gcd_three(646, 1406, 4218)
## [1] 38

is_prime

check all number whether is prime

  1. input(x)
    1. x: atomic vector and dimension = 1
    2. get the length of x
    3. create a return variable and named output
  2. use for (i in 1:x_len) loop, check every number of x, use x[i].
    1. check number whether is positive integer. [if (x[i] <= 0 | x[i]%%1 != 0)]
      1. (if) number is not positive integer, return FALSE
      2. (else) go to next step
    2. check number whether is 2. [if (x[i] == 2)]
      1. (if) number is 2, return TRUE
      2. (else) go to next step
    3. use for (j in 2:b) loop, check there is any divisor in 2:b. (b<- x[i] 1)
      1. (if) there exist a divisor(not prime),
      2. then return False. Break the loop.
      3. (else) return true and check next number in 2:b
  3. After checking all the number, return the output
    1. Return: logical vector and dimension = 1

get_factors

Find all prime factors of x

  1. Input(x)
    1. x: atomic vector and dimension = 1
    2. store x to a test variable n
    3. create a return variable and named output_prime
  2. check the number whether is numerical. [if (is.numeric(n) == FALSE)]
    1. (if) it is not numerical number -> stop with an error message
    2. (else) go to next step
  3. check the number whether is positive integer. [if (n <= 0 | n%%1 != 0)]
    1. (if) it is not positive integer -> stop with an error message
    2. (else) go to next step
  4. check the number whether is 1. [if (n == 1)]
    1. (if) it is 1 -> stop with an error message
    2. (else) go to next step
  5. check the number whether is prime number. [if (is_prime(n) == TRUE)]
    1. (if) it is prime number -> return itself
    2. (else) go to next step, find the prime factors of x
  6. use while (j <= n) loop, and let j = 2. Checking if there exists a prime factor between 2 and n.
    1. (if) j is a prime factor between j and n.
      1. store j into output_prime. [output_prime <- append(output_prime, j)]
      2. get a new n <- n/j and store to n. so we can find another prime factor.
    2. check next j. [j <- j + 1]
  7. After checking all the prime factor
    1. return the output_prime
    2. output: positive integer and dimension = 1
